WEBVTT

00:04.308 --> 00:06.267
- This is Auggie.

00:06.310 --> 00:09.487
- The foster family felt
he would be too much to handle.

00:09.531 --> 00:12.447
- We'll do it.
We'll foster him.

00:12.490 --> 00:14.362
<i>- I have to make some changes
around here.</i>

00:14.405 --> 00:17.800
<i>The ED has not been running
as effectively as it could be.</i>

00:17.843 --> 00:19.149
A good leader takes
responsibility

00:19.193 --> 00:21.282
for everything that happens
on his watch.

00:21.325 --> 00:23.849
<i>- I'm testing a brand-new
heart failure drug.</i>

00:23.893 --> 00:25.373
With some hard work,

00:25.416 --> 00:26.678
I think we could fill this
trial in a matter of weeks,

00:26.722 --> 00:28.115
not months.

00:28.158 --> 00:31.074
<i>- Why do you do
the one-night stands?</i>

00:31.118 --> 00:33.294
They all end up the same.

00:33.337 --> 00:35.209
<i>With you alone.</i>

00:36.558 --> 00:38.777
[laughter]

00:38.821 --> 00:41.824
- There she is!
Our fearless leader.

00:41.867 --> 00:44.218
- Returning from exile.
[laughter]

00:44.261 --> 00:46.655
- How you doing, Michael?
You look good. You look fit.

00:46.698 --> 00:50.180
- Moving back home.
Solid meals instead of takeout.

00:50.224 --> 00:52.182
The only positive thing
about being furloughed.

00:52.226 --> 00:53.705
- The hospital lifted
restriction

00:53.749 --> 00:55.794
on nonessential personnel
on-site.

00:55.838 --> 00:57.187
- Mm-hmm.

00:57.231 --> 00:59.624
- Device reps are being allowed
into the OR.

00:59.668 --> 01:01.148
- Gotta go, Ma.
Catch you later.

01:01.191 --> 01:02.540
- All righty.
- Doc C.

01:02.584 --> 01:04.368
- I'll see ya.

01:04.412 --> 01:05.848
Oh, Sharon.
- [chuckles]

01:05.891 --> 01:08.633
- It is so great to see you,
to see you in the flesh.

01:08.677 --> 01:11.201
- Yeah, thanks, Daniel,
and it's about time.

01:11.245 --> 01:13.638
COVID protocols have been
working for months.

01:13.682 --> 01:15.118
Even with my diabetes,

01:15.162 --> 01:17.251
there was no reason
for me to stay at home.

01:17.294 --> 01:19.557
- Watch out, Med.
She's back!

01:19.601 --> 01:22.560
- [laughs]
- You, uh,

01:22.604 --> 01:23.909
care to join me
for a nasal swab?

01:23.953 --> 01:26.216
- Would love to.
- After you.

01:26.260 --> 01:29.219
<i>[soft upbeat music]</i>

01:29.263 --> 01:33.180
<i>♪</i>

01:33.223 --> 01:34.181
- Ooh.
- Oh.

01:34.224 --> 01:36.139
- Sorry. Good morning.
- Hi.

01:36.183 --> 01:37.227
- Good morning.

01:37.271 --> 01:38.228
- Sorry, I didn't see you
coming up.

01:38.272 --> 01:40.404
- No, I didn't see you
going in.

01:40.448 --> 01:43.581
- Well, no harm, no foul.
- Mm-hmm.

01:43.625 --> 01:45.583
See you around.
- Yeah, catch you later.

01:45.627 --> 01:48.151
- See ya.
- Okay.

01:48.195 --> 01:50.893
- I'm not gonna say anything,
but I saw that.

01:50.936 --> 01:52.590
- You saw what?

01:52.634 --> 01:53.939
We just caught each other
by surprise.

01:53.983 --> 01:55.419
- Right.

01:55.463 --> 01:57.160
Did you want me to pass him
a note in homeroom, too?

01:57.204 --> 01:58.640
- Ha, ha.
- Maggie?

01:58.683 --> 02:00.294
- One second.

02:00.337 --> 02:02.426
- We're friends.
That's it.

02:02.470 --> 02:04.559
- Mm-hmm?
- Mm-hmm.

02:04.602 --> 02:05.734
- Mm...

02:05.777 --> 02:07.866
hypothetically though,
if it were to be

02:07.910 --> 02:09.781
that kind of attraction,
what do you think?

02:09.825 --> 02:12.436
- I don't know, Nat.
Crockett?

02:12.480 --> 02:15.744
Is he really your type?

02:15.787 --> 02:16.832
Oh.

02:16.875 --> 02:21.793
<i>♪</i>

02:21.837 --> 02:24.448
- Sorry,
I just gotta deal with this

02:24.492 --> 02:26.798
before it gets out of hand.

02:26.842 --> 02:29.714
Done.
Last time I pick up the phone.

02:29.758 --> 02:30.846
Promise.

02:30.889 --> 02:32.413
- Trust me,
I know how busy you are.

02:32.456 --> 02:35.198
I really appreciate you making
the time to check in.

02:35.242 --> 02:38.419
- Only way to cross it off
the list is to get it done.

02:38.462 --> 02:39.855
Like dealing
with expense reports,

02:39.898 --> 02:42.858
managing doctor-nurse
staffing levels,

02:42.901 --> 02:45.861
let alone a distribution plan
for a possible COVID vaccine.

02:45.904 --> 02:47.950
- Wow. A lot of stuff.

02:47.993 --> 02:50.866
- Yeah, but I can handle it.

02:50.909 --> 02:54.261
I guess my--my years
on active duty,

02:54.304 --> 02:55.827
the COs I learned under,

02:55.871 --> 02:58.482
chief of the ED
is what I've been trained for.

02:58.526 --> 02:59.831
You know,

02:59.875 --> 03:02.921
this is an opportunity
for everyone to step up.

03:02.965 --> 03:04.706
We need to do the job
better than ever.

03:04.749 --> 03:08.579
- Buddy, I think it's such an
admirable attitude, you know?

03:08.623 --> 03:10.494
It just might be a good idea

03:10.538 --> 03:11.800
to keep it in the back
of your mind, you know,

03:11.843 --> 03:14.629
not everybody is as, um...
[clicks tongue]

03:14.672 --> 03:17.762
combat-tested, if you will,
as you are.

03:17.806 --> 03:18.981
People are just exhausted.

03:19.024 --> 03:21.679
For most of them,
doing better, I mean,

03:21.723 --> 03:23.246
is, like,
getting through the day.

03:23.290 --> 03:25.335
- Yeah.

03:25.379 --> 03:29.470
Listen, my first tour,
I really struggled.

03:29.513 --> 03:33.300
Far from home, no sleep...

03:33.343 --> 03:35.040
Marines dying every day.

03:35.084 --> 03:37.347
I went to my CO,
told him I was exhausted.

03:37.391 --> 03:38.870
You know what he said?

03:38.914 --> 03:43.440
"Now's not the time, Choi.
You can rest when it's over."

03:43.484 --> 03:44.441
- I get it.

03:44.485 --> 03:46.487
- Look, Dr. Charles,

03:46.530 --> 03:48.271
I know I'm not gonna be able
to please everyone,

03:48.315 --> 03:50.491
but that's not the mission.

03:50.534 --> 03:51.970
I was promoted
to right the ship.

03:52.014 --> 03:52.971
<i>[phone chimes, buzzes]</i>

03:53.015 --> 03:55.365
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

03:55.409 --> 03:58.281
<i>[phone chiming]
- You gonna get that?</i>

03:58.325 --> 04:02.677
<i>♪</i>

04:02.720 --> 04:04.113
- I gotta cut this short.

04:04.156 --> 04:06.463
- Do your thing, man.
Appreciate you stopping by.

04:06.507 --> 04:08.813
- Sure thing.

04:08.857 --> 04:15.864
<i>♪</i>

04:20.782 --> 04:24.525
Dr. Driskell,
what do you got?

04:24.568 --> 04:26.744
- Drew Corbett,
62-year-old male,

04:26.788 --> 04:29.573
eight days-plus presenting
with COVID symptoms.

04:29.617 --> 04:32.097
In and out of respiratory
failure the past three days.

04:32.141 --> 04:33.360
- All right.

04:33.403 --> 04:35.971
- Drew married
his high school sweetheart.

04:36.014 --> 04:38.365
His wife, his two kids,
his three grandkids,

04:38.408 --> 04:39.670
FaceTime him every day.

04:39.714 --> 04:41.324
- Labs?

04:41.368 --> 04:42.847
- Suggestive of
a cytokine storm.

04:42.891 --> 04:44.327
We're trying to get it
under control,

04:44.371 --> 04:45.937
but his vitals
are still unstable.

04:45.981 --> 04:47.069
- What do you want to do?

04:47.112 --> 04:48.592
- Keep him on a high-flow O2,

04:48.636 --> 04:49.941
start him on a COVID cocktail.

04:49.985 --> 04:51.029
- Good.

04:51.073 --> 04:54.772
- V-tach. <i>
[EKG flatlining]</i>

04:54.816 --> 04:56.078
No pulse.

04:56.121 --> 04:57.601
- Open his airway.
Bag him.

04:57.645 --> 04:58.907
I'm on compressions.

04:58.950 --> 05:01.562
- No.
Hold compressions.

05:01.605 --> 05:03.955
Charge to 200.
Draw up an amp of epi.

05:03.999 --> 05:05.043
- He's unstable.

05:05.087 --> 05:06.654
Needs to maintain
cardiac profusion.

05:06.697 --> 05:08.960
- No compressions.
Hospital policy.

05:09.004 --> 05:11.006
CPR aerosolizes the virus,
puts you all at risk.

05:11.049 --> 05:12.355
You know that.

05:12.399 --> 05:14.401
<i>[AED charging and whining]
- Paddles.</i>

05:14.444 --> 05:16.881
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

05:16.925 --> 05:17.882
Clear.

05:17.926 --> 05:20.798
<i>♪</i>

05:20.842 --> 05:21.843
<i>[AED thuds]</i>

05:21.886 --> 05:23.453
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

05:23.497 --> 05:25.455
- Amp of epi,
recharge the paddles.

05:25.499 --> 05:28.763
<i>[AED charging and whining]
Shock him again.</i>

05:28.806 --> 05:30.025
Shock him again!

05:30.068 --> 05:31.461
- Clear.

05:31.505 --> 05:33.115
<i>♪</i>

05:33.158 --> 05:34.638
<i>[AED thuds]</i>

05:34.682 --> 05:36.379
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

05:36.423 --> 05:37.989
- Please let me do
compressions.

05:38.033 --> 05:39.164
It'll keep his heart alive.

05:39.208 --> 05:40.992
- No.
Run it again.

05:41.036 --> 05:43.821
<i>[AED charging and whining]
- Clear.</i>

05:43.865 --> 05:45.432
<i>[AED thuds]</i>

05:45.475 --> 05:48.522
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

05:48.565 --> 05:55.572
<i>♪</i>

05:58.053 --> 05:59.750
We did everything we could.

05:59.794 --> 06:03.537
<i>♪</i>

06:03.580 --> 06:04.668
- [scoffs]

06:04.712 --> 06:10.413
<i>♪</i>

06:19.248 --> 06:21.990
[indistinct chatter]

06:22.033 --> 06:24.471
- Ms. Goodwin, welcome back.
- Thank you.

06:24.514 --> 06:26.995
- I haven't had the chance yet
to compile the nightly numbers,

06:27.038 --> 06:28.126
but I'll get them to you ASAP.

06:28.170 --> 06:29.606
- No hurry.
We can go over them later.

06:29.650 --> 06:32.000
I'm just making rounds,
saying hello to everyone.

06:32.043 --> 06:33.262
- [chuckles]

06:33.305 --> 06:35.569
[indistinct chatter]

06:35.612 --> 06:38.615
Mags, who's up?
- Uh, Treatment 5.

06:38.659 --> 06:41.009
Just sent it to your iPad.

06:41.052 --> 06:42.576
<i>[notification chimes]
- Thanks.</i>

06:42.619 --> 06:44.447
And hey, I'd like to get the
treatment rooms turned over

06:44.491 --> 06:46.536
within ten minutes of a patient
being discharged.

06:46.580 --> 06:49.017
- With UV sanitizing?
- Yeah.

06:49.060 --> 06:52.020
- I can't get it in under 15.
- Try.

06:52.063 --> 06:54.631
And please make sure the
equipment carts are restocked

06:54.675 --> 06:56.459
three times per shift.

06:56.503 --> 06:58.026
- Okay.

06:59.506 --> 07:00.507
- Hey, Mr. Lowry.

07:00.550 --> 07:02.160
- Dr. Lowry.

07:02.204 --> 07:04.293
Plastic surgeon.

07:04.336 --> 07:06.251
- Excuse me.
Dr. Lowry.

07:06.295 --> 07:07.427
What's going on?

07:07.470 --> 07:09.254
- I became lightheaded
during a surgery.

07:09.298 --> 07:12.083
Minor procedure, too.
Lipoma removal.

07:12.127 --> 07:15.086
Fatty tumor. Stain on the body.
Had to go.

07:15.130 --> 07:17.611
Anyway, I felt myself going
limp before I could remove it.

07:17.654 --> 07:18.960
Didn't lose consciousness.

07:19.003 --> 07:22.137
Nevertheless, my surgical
assistant overreacted.

07:22.180 --> 07:23.138
Called 911.

07:23.181 --> 07:24.269
- She did the right thing

07:24.313 --> 07:25.619
for your safety
and your patient's.

07:25.662 --> 07:28.448
- I am the patient.

07:28.491 --> 07:30.972
- I meant who you were
operating on.

07:31.015 --> 07:33.322
- Yeah, that's me.

07:33.365 --> 07:34.976
- You were operating
on yourself?

07:35.019 --> 07:36.499
- [chuckling]
Of course.

07:36.543 --> 07:38.545
I'm not gonna settle for
anything less than perfection.

07:38.588 --> 07:41.330
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

07:41.373 --> 07:43.463
- May I?
- Mm.

07:43.506 --> 07:45.987
<i>♪</i>

07:46.030 --> 07:47.510
- Um...

07:47.554 --> 07:50.208
I'm seeing other scars here.

07:50.252 --> 07:52.167
These pectoral implants?
- Indeed.

07:52.210 --> 07:53.516
Very proud of them.

07:53.560 --> 07:54.648
- Oh.

07:54.691 --> 07:56.258
Liposuction?

07:56.301 --> 07:58.434
- Had a six-pack.
Now it's an eight-pack.

07:58.478 --> 08:01.176
Filler, too.
Can't tell, can you?

08:01.219 --> 08:02.438
- Everything you've done here

08:02.482 --> 08:03.613
looks--
- Perfect.

08:03.657 --> 08:06.486
I told you,
I know what I'm doing.

08:06.529 --> 08:08.009
- Even so, your BP's soft.

08:08.052 --> 08:10.620
Likely hypovolemia from blood
loss during the procedure.

08:10.664 --> 08:12.230
- I'm well aware.
I am a doctor.

08:12.274 --> 08:14.537
So hang a liter of LR
and I'll get outta here.

08:14.581 --> 08:17.018
- Actually,
I prefer normal saline.

08:17.061 --> 08:18.454
Also, let's type and cross
two units of blood

08:18.498 --> 08:20.064
to replenish the loss.

08:20.108 --> 08:22.023
As for the lipoma,
we can finish that up.

08:22.066 --> 08:23.546
I'll call Plastics
for a consult.

08:23.590 --> 08:25.287
- No, thanks.

08:25.330 --> 08:27.115
You do it.

08:27.158 --> 08:29.030
- It's best
a surgeon handle this.

08:29.073 --> 08:30.292
- Disagree.

08:30.335 --> 08:32.468
Surgeons don't take advice
very well,

08:32.512 --> 08:33.774
especially from other surgeons.

08:33.817 --> 08:35.384
It's okay.

08:35.427 --> 08:37.473
All you have to do
is follow my instructions.

08:37.517 --> 08:40.258
<i>♪</i>

08:40.302 --> 08:42.609
- Dr. Charles,
I got a patient for you.

08:42.652 --> 08:45.786
Todd Lowry, 43,
plastic surgeon.

08:45.829 --> 08:48.266
He's been operating on himself,
a lot.

08:48.310 --> 08:50.442
Doesn't think twice
about the risks.

08:50.486 --> 08:53.141
- Interesting.

08:53.184 --> 08:54.577
Doctors,
we know best, right?

08:54.621 --> 08:58.276
Keep diagnosing ourselves,
writing our own scripts.

08:58.320 --> 09:00.061
Been guilty of both myself.

09:00.104 --> 09:03.151
- Sure, we take some liberties,
but Todd is way past that.

09:03.194 --> 09:05.022
These aren't just
Botox injections,

09:05.066 --> 09:06.589
they're invasive operations.

09:06.633 --> 09:08.243
- Huh.

09:08.286 --> 09:11.725
Let me, uh, let me have a chat
with him, check back with you.

09:11.768 --> 09:13.161
- Thanks.

09:13.204 --> 09:15.642
<i>[EKG beeping]</i>

09:15.685 --> 09:18.775
- Does that hurt, Isabella?
- Sort of.

09:18.819 --> 09:21.169
Um, it's not pain
as much as just tightness.

09:21.212 --> 09:23.650
- All right, well,
I'm not feeling anything overt,

09:23.693 --> 09:25.608
but you are really clenching
your ab muscles.

09:25.652 --> 09:28.132
Why don't you try to take
a deep breath and relax?

09:28.176 --> 09:30.613
- Relax, yeah.
I wish.

09:30.657 --> 09:32.528
2020 kind of took that
off the table.

09:32.572 --> 09:34.138
- [chuckles softly]

09:34.182 --> 09:38.360
- Stomach's been a mess
for a few months now.

09:38.403 --> 09:39.709
I should've come in sooner.

09:39.753 --> 09:41.189
- Well, you're here now.

09:41.232 --> 09:42.712
All right, we're just gonna do
a quick X-ray,

09:42.756 --> 09:46.194
so if you could stay still
for a second.

09:46.237 --> 09:49.066
[machinery whirs]

09:53.418 --> 09:55.682
- So, um, what did you see?

09:55.725 --> 09:57.771
- Well,
your bowel does look distended

09:57.814 --> 10:00.469
and there is a moderate amount
of stool.

10:00.512 --> 10:03.385
When was your last movement?
- A few days ago.

10:03.428 --> 10:07.302
Actually, they've been here
or there for a while.

10:07.345 --> 10:09.304
Could I just be constipated?

10:09.347 --> 10:11.349
- Well, I do want to run
some labs and get a CT,

10:11.393 --> 10:13.395
but yes,
this could just be stress

10:13.438 --> 10:15.136
causing you to clench
the muscles in the back

10:15.179 --> 10:16.528
the way
you're clenching your abs.

10:16.572 --> 10:17.834
- [chuckles]

10:17.878 --> 10:20.228
It's not the tight ass
I would've wished for,

10:20.271 --> 10:22.534
but then again,
it's still a Zoom world

10:22.578 --> 10:24.580
so I guess no one's really
looking anyway.

10:24.624 --> 10:25.929
- There you go.

10:25.973 --> 10:27.496
All right, a nurse will be by
in a minute, okay?

10:27.539 --> 10:29.280
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

10:33.154 --> 10:36.200
- Ah, so, Doris, I need--
- No.

10:36.244 --> 10:37.245
Mm-mm.
That's your sweet voice.

10:37.288 --> 10:38.681
I know what that means.

10:38.725 --> 10:41.249
[sighs]
What's he want now?

10:41.292 --> 10:43.555
- [sighs]
He put together a list.

10:43.599 --> 10:46.733
- You know, I was never a fan
of Dr. Lanik, but Ethan?

10:46.776 --> 10:49.300
[speaks Italian]
- Whatever that means.

10:49.344 --> 10:51.128
- That he sucks.
- Oh.

10:51.172 --> 10:52.434
- I've been learning Italian.

10:52.477 --> 10:54.697
- I noticed.
You're planning a trip?

10:54.741 --> 10:56.873
- I took an ancestry DNA test
a few weeks ago.

10:56.917 --> 10:58.745
I knew my grandparents were
from Chile.

10:58.788 --> 11:02.705
I had no idea though that their
grandparents were from Naples.

11:02.749 --> 11:05.273
- Oh, that's cool.
I've never been to Italy.

11:05.316 --> 11:06.796
It's on the list, though.

11:06.840 --> 11:08.885
Until then, you, Trini,
and Hank take the first three.

11:08.929 --> 11:10.626
I'll take the rest.

11:15.500 --> 11:17.328
<i>- So no running
on the treadmill?</i>

11:17.372 --> 11:18.547
- Nope.

11:18.590 --> 11:20.592
Only bloodwork and an echo,
Mr. Gessner.

11:20.636 --> 11:22.203
<i>- What about the meds?</i>

11:22.246 --> 11:25.336
<i>Hospital's pushing aspirin
for 30 bucks a pop.</i>

11:25.380 --> 11:26.903
<i>Heart disease pill
you're selling?</i>

11:26.947 --> 11:29.166
<i>Bet I'd probably need a second
mortgage to pay for that.</i>

11:29.210 --> 11:30.385
- If you qualify,

11:30.428 --> 11:33.649
the pharmaceutical company
covers all costs.

11:33.693 --> 11:35.695
<i>- I like that.</i>

11:35.738 --> 11:39.742
- So, uh, what do you say?
Can I enroll you?

11:39.786 --> 11:41.613
<i>- No.
Sorry, too risky.</i>

11:41.657 --> 11:44.486
- What? How?
Mr. Gessner.

11:44.529 --> 11:46.183
<i>- You know,
my ticker's not great,</i>

11:46.227 --> 11:49.230
<i>but the pills I'm on
are working.</i>

11:49.273 --> 11:52.929
<i>COVID, though?
That bug is a wildcard. I--</i>

11:52.973 --> 11:54.975
<i>no, no, no hospitals
till I've got the vaccine.</i>

11:55.018 --> 11:56.150
- Please don't hang up.

11:56.193 --> 11:57.891
The COVID ward
is completely contained.

11:57.934 --> 12:00.415
No contact with
where you will be in the ED.

12:00.458 --> 12:02.678
<i>- Yeah, says you.
- Hey, it's the truth.</i>

12:02.722 --> 12:05.812
I'm there all day.
I've never felt safer.

12:05.855 --> 12:07.988
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

12:08.031 --> 12:09.772
<i>- Okay, I guess I can come in
this afternoon.</i>

12:09.816 --> 12:13.558
- Mr. Gessner, thank you.
I'll see you later.

12:13.602 --> 12:14.821
[chuckles]

12:14.864 --> 12:16.953
- Nice job.

12:16.997 --> 12:18.476
He almost got away.

12:18.520 --> 12:20.827
- God, too many of 'em have.

12:20.870 --> 12:23.525
That's why I'm behind
on my quota.

12:23.568 --> 12:26.006
Millions suffer
from heart failure, April.

12:26.049 --> 12:29.444
I had no idea how difficult
it'd be finding them.

12:29.487 --> 12:30.532
- I don't get it.

12:30.575 --> 12:31.663
We get cases in the ED
every day,

12:31.707 --> 12:33.274
not to mention Cardiology.

12:33.317 --> 12:34.623
- And they've thrown me a bunch
of files.

12:34.666 --> 12:37.713
Unfortunately, the study's
exclusionary criteria

12:37.757 --> 12:40.803
weed out a lot of patients.

12:40.847 --> 12:42.762
I am meeting a cardiologist
at Chicago Congress

12:42.805 --> 12:44.067
later this morning,

12:44.111 --> 12:46.983
hoping he'll throw me
a few patients, but--

12:47.027 --> 12:50.682
and I'll, uh, keep pitching
the Med patients that are left.

12:50.726 --> 12:53.816
- I'd like to help.

12:53.860 --> 12:56.863
- Yeah?
- When I was in the COVID ward,

12:56.906 --> 12:58.603
I felt like I was a part
of something

12:58.647 --> 13:00.692
so much bigger than myself.

13:00.736 --> 13:03.043
I'd like to feel that again.

13:03.086 --> 13:05.306
I'll make time.

13:05.349 --> 13:07.482
- Welcome aboard.

13:07.525 --> 13:09.049
- All right.
[both chuckle]

13:09.092 --> 13:11.616
So why don't you focus
on your meeting?

13:11.660 --> 13:15.925
And I will reach out to
the rest of these Med patients.

13:15.969 --> 13:18.928
- All right.
- Great.

13:18.972 --> 13:20.756
- All right.

13:20.800 --> 13:23.411
<i>♪</i>

13:23.454 --> 13:24.586
[sighs]

13:24.629 --> 13:31.636
<i>♪</i>

13:32.812 --> 13:33.900
- Dr. Manning,

13:33.943 --> 13:35.945
all this, it's...

13:35.989 --> 13:38.078
- Tumor.

13:38.121 --> 13:42.865
Her abdomen is full of cancer.

13:42.909 --> 13:47.652
<i>♪</i>

13:52.266 --> 13:54.398
- Cancer?
Um, I don't understand.

13:54.442 --> 13:57.967
I'm--I'm only 21.

13:58.011 --> 14:01.231
I should've come in the moment
that I felt something was off,

14:01.275 --> 14:03.451
but I live at home.

14:03.494 --> 14:05.148
Both my parents are high risk
for COVID.

14:05.192 --> 14:07.237
I just didn't want to bring it
into the house.

14:07.281 --> 14:09.065
- We understand.

14:09.109 --> 14:11.024
You thought you were doing
what was right.

14:13.940 --> 14:15.245
- Am I gonna die?

14:15.289 --> 14:16.986
- No. Hey.

14:17.030 --> 14:19.206
Look,
we'll confer with Oncology,

14:19.249 --> 14:23.384
but I believe that this section
and then this section too

14:23.427 --> 14:24.994
are amenable to resection.

14:25.038 --> 14:26.343
- Resection?

14:26.387 --> 14:29.607
Um, that means surgery, right?
- That's right.

14:29.651 --> 14:31.087
The more tumor I remove now,

14:31.131 --> 14:33.263
the better your position
for cancer treatment later.

14:33.307 --> 14:35.831
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

14:35.875 --> 14:37.093
- Okay.

14:37.137 --> 14:38.965
<i>♪</i>

14:39.008 --> 14:40.401
- Hey.

14:40.444 --> 14:43.926
I know you're scared,
but you can win this fight.

14:43.970 --> 14:48.235
<i>♪</i>

14:48.278 --> 14:51.934
- Wow, that's impressive.

14:51.978 --> 14:53.588
I mean, not just
the attention to detail,

14:53.631 --> 14:57.374
but I mean, the focus that must
be required to achieve that.

14:57.418 --> 15:00.987
- Flattery.
Really?

15:01.030 --> 15:02.597
You're the head of Psychiatry.

15:02.640 --> 15:04.555
I'd figured you'd use something
a little more clever

15:04.599 --> 15:05.556
to get inside my head.

15:05.600 --> 15:06.993
- Oh, come on.

15:07.036 --> 15:08.559
We're just, uh, we're just
having a little chat.

15:08.603 --> 15:10.083
- Okay, fine.
I'll buy it.

15:10.126 --> 15:11.301
But scrap the pats on the back.

15:11.345 --> 15:14.609
I know I'm good,
you don't need to tell me.

15:14.652 --> 15:17.568
- You mind if I sit?

15:21.921 --> 15:23.574
- This is invasive.

15:23.618 --> 15:26.621
Tumor already has
a blood supply,

15:26.664 --> 15:28.405
has invaded
the surrounding tissues.

15:28.449 --> 15:30.364
- Yes, but there's
two clear areas of focus

15:30.407 --> 15:31.887
around the left lobe
of the liver

15:31.931 --> 15:35.195
and the same with the inferior
poles of the kidneys here.

15:35.238 --> 15:37.023
- I don't think so.

15:37.066 --> 15:40.983
My experience, CTs are rarely
as accurate as they appear.

15:41.027 --> 15:43.072
Tumor already looks like
a nightmare.

15:43.116 --> 15:46.510
What's actually going on inside
is a disaster.

15:46.554 --> 15:48.991
- Okay, look,
all due respect, Dr. Gillen,

15:49.035 --> 15:52.038
I'm not pushing to operate
to boost my résumé.

15:52.081 --> 15:53.909
I want to save Isabella's life.

15:53.953 --> 15:55.258
- So do I.

15:55.302 --> 15:58.609
This CT, though,
worst-case territory.

15:58.653 --> 16:01.569
A biopsy
and appropriate chemo regimen

16:01.612 --> 16:03.397
are the safest first step.

16:03.440 --> 16:06.530
Perhaps surgery down the line.
- Perhaps?

16:06.574 --> 16:08.576
- She's very sick, Dr. Manning.

16:08.619 --> 16:10.186
If we'd been able
to treat her earlier--

16:10.230 --> 16:11.535
- Well, we weren't.

16:11.579 --> 16:13.189
- I understand.

16:13.233 --> 16:16.932
And in that time,
her cancer progressed too far.

16:16.976 --> 16:23.939
<i>♪</i>

16:23.983 --> 16:25.985
- So that's it?

16:26.028 --> 16:29.031
- Dr. Gillen has her opinion,
I have mine.

16:29.075 --> 16:35.995
<i>♪</i>

16:36.038 --> 16:37.387
- So how'd it go?

16:37.431 --> 16:39.128
Did Dr. Lowry, plastic surgeon,
shrink himself?

16:39.172 --> 16:41.174
- Not really his priority.

16:41.217 --> 16:43.045
- Putting him on a five-day,
then?

16:43.089 --> 16:45.134
- A psych hold?
Why?

16:45.178 --> 16:47.441
- Dr. Charles,
he cut himself open.

16:47.484 --> 16:49.573
- Yeah,
because of body dysmorphia.

16:49.617 --> 16:51.662
Which is driven, ironically,
by a desire

16:51.706 --> 16:54.100
to perfect his body,
not to hurt himself.

16:54.143 --> 16:55.536
- Maybe not intentionally,

16:55.579 --> 16:58.365
but that perfectionism clearly
clouds his judgment.

16:58.408 --> 16:59.583
We need to step in.

16:59.627 --> 17:00.976
- Well, the thing is,

17:01.020 --> 17:03.065
BDD isn't something
that we can just fix.

17:03.109 --> 17:04.371
You know, Todd's gotta develop

17:04.414 --> 17:06.982
an entirely new perspective
on his body.

17:07.026 --> 17:08.592
That's gonna take time,
you know?

17:08.636 --> 17:09.724
- You know a guy like Todd

17:09.767 --> 17:11.508
isn't gonna go to therapy
voluntarily.

17:11.552 --> 17:13.423
We intervene now
or this just gets worse.

17:13.467 --> 17:15.382
- I hear you and will, uh,

17:15.425 --> 17:17.079
will take that
under advisement.

17:18.646 --> 17:20.082
- Hey, Mags,
where are we on those changes

17:20.126 --> 17:21.562
to the nursing room team?

17:21.605 --> 17:25.348
- Ethan, we're short-staffed.
I'm doing what I can.

17:25.392 --> 17:27.785
The other nurses, too.

17:27.829 --> 17:29.613
<i>[phone ringing]
It's Ben.</i>

17:29.657 --> 17:31.224
Give me two minutes?
- Yeah.

17:31.267 --> 17:33.269
Just get the changes done,
okay?

17:33.313 --> 17:35.619
- Yeah.

17:35.663 --> 17:37.273
Hey, babe.
What's up?

17:37.317 --> 17:40.276
<i>- Auggie's not feeling so hot.
Temp's a little high.</i>

17:40.320 --> 17:43.105
<i>He hasn't thrown up,
but feels like he might.</i>

17:43.149 --> 17:45.151
- How's his energy? <i>
- Low.</i>

17:45.194 --> 17:47.283
<i>Doesn't even have enough
strength for "Minecraft."</i>

17:47.327 --> 17:48.545
<i>That's a red flag.</i>

17:48.589 --> 17:52.245
- Can you put him on? <i>
- Sure.</i>

17:52.288 --> 17:54.421
- Hey, little man.

17:54.464 --> 17:56.727
<i>- Sorry for bothering you
at work.</i>

17:56.771 --> 17:59.817
- There's nothing
to apologize for.

17:59.861 --> 18:02.037
Can you do me a favor?

18:02.081 --> 18:04.822
Can you lean in real close
to the phone

18:04.866 --> 18:07.695
and look into the lens
so I can see your eyes?

18:10.089 --> 18:14.310
Okay. Thanks, honey.
You can go back to resting.

18:14.354 --> 18:17.792
<i>♪</i>

18:17.835 --> 18:20.577
<i>- So what do you think?</i>

18:20.621 --> 18:23.189
- Natalie needs to take a look.

18:23.232 --> 18:25.495
<i>- Okay.
I'll bring him in.</i>

18:25.539 --> 18:27.541
- Yeah.

18:27.584 --> 18:30.674
<i>- Are we there?</i>

18:30.718 --> 18:33.634
- I hope not.

18:33.677 --> 18:35.766
<i>♪</i>

18:35.810 --> 18:39.379
- You've been seeing results?
- So far, yes.

18:39.422 --> 18:40.554
Study's still small,

18:40.597 --> 18:42.556
but the data has been
very encouraging.

18:42.599 --> 18:45.646
- It always is
in the early phases.

18:45.689 --> 18:49.693
But I've seen a lot of heart
failure trials come and go.

18:49.737 --> 18:52.174
Is this the real deal?
- I hope so.

18:52.218 --> 18:54.524
Yesterday,
I treated a woman in the ED.

18:54.568 --> 18:56.178
Massive MI.

18:56.222 --> 18:57.527
She's now on a vent in the CCU

18:57.571 --> 18:59.225
and the odds are not
on her side.

19:02.576 --> 19:04.491
But if this oral inotrope
works,

19:04.534 --> 19:07.711
what happened to her may not
have to happen to anyone else.

19:07.755 --> 19:09.713
- Okay.

19:09.757 --> 19:11.193
Sold.

19:11.237 --> 19:12.194
I'm in.

19:12.238 --> 19:13.891
- Wonderful.

19:13.935 --> 19:15.197
Thank you, Dr. Mayfield.

19:15.241 --> 19:17.156
Your patients will really help
the study.

19:17.199 --> 19:19.549
- That's great
for your hospital.

19:19.593 --> 19:21.551
Now let's discuss mine.

19:21.595 --> 19:25.773
How's 30% sound?

19:25.816 --> 19:27.514
- Sorry.
Uh, 30% of what?

19:27.557 --> 19:31.387
- Your patient enrollment fee.
- [sighs]

19:31.431 --> 19:33.868
<i>♪</i>

19:33.911 --> 19:36.827
A kickback?
- That's a harsh word.

19:36.871 --> 19:39.395
I prefer we call it
quid pro quo.

19:39.439 --> 19:40.396
- Well,
call it whatever you want.

19:40.440 --> 19:42.442
It's unethical.

19:42.485 --> 19:43.747
I can't do it.

19:43.791 --> 19:46.228
- I'm afraid I can't help you.

19:46.272 --> 19:47.708
- Look, I'm from Canaryville.

19:47.751 --> 19:49.188
I get that one hand washes
the other,

19:49.231 --> 19:50.580
but that's
neighborhood politics.

19:50.624 --> 19:51.929
This is science.

19:51.973 --> 19:54.802
- Yeah, this isn't Chicago Med,
Dr. Halstead.

19:54.845 --> 19:57.587
There's no university backing
or Wall Street investment

19:57.631 --> 19:59.807
or billionaire benefactors.

19:59.850 --> 20:02.418
I cannot afford
to give away patients for free.

20:02.462 --> 20:04.681
I'm sorry.

20:04.725 --> 20:08.598
Good luck with your trial.

20:08.642 --> 20:10.296
- Appreciate your time,
Dr. Mayfield.

20:10.339 --> 20:16.345
<i>♪</i>

20:16.389 --> 20:20.741
- Ms. Goodwin, I've discussed
all the risks with Isabella.

20:20.784 --> 20:22.699
She wants to proceed
with surgery

20:22.743 --> 20:24.440
and I'm confident I can do it.

20:24.484 --> 20:27.269
- This isn't about
your ability, Dr. Marcel,

20:27.313 --> 20:29.880
it's about the state
of Isabella's cancer.

20:29.924 --> 20:32.318
Dr. Gillen is the head
of Oncology.

20:32.361 --> 20:34.581
I will not override
her decision.

20:34.624 --> 20:35.886
- Ms. Goodwin,

20:35.930 --> 20:38.324
without being able to resect
part of the tumor,

20:38.367 --> 20:39.673
the chemo won't work.

20:39.716 --> 20:41.283
Please.

20:41.327 --> 20:45.200
We are where we are because
she was protecting her family.

20:45.244 --> 20:46.854
She deserves our help.

20:46.897 --> 20:49.291
- This virus...

20:49.335 --> 20:51.467
not only is it still
killing people,

20:51.511 --> 20:54.514
but it's forced thousands
of others like Isabella

20:54.557 --> 20:57.473
to delay or even
interrupt treatment.

20:57.517 --> 21:00.650
Not just cancer,
but all chronic illnesses.

21:00.694 --> 21:05.525
Look, I wish I could help
every patient.

21:05.568 --> 21:08.310
But the honest reality is

21:08.354 --> 21:11.574
some won't be able to be saved.

21:11.618 --> 21:15.883
<i>♪</i>

21:15.926 --> 21:18.799
- World kinda sucks right now,
Ms. Goodwin.

21:18.842 --> 21:21.323
- Yes, it does.

21:21.367 --> 21:22.672
Yes, it does.

21:22.716 --> 21:24.457
- Thank you.

21:24.500 --> 21:29.984
<i>♪</i>

21:30.027 --> 21:32.291
- [sighs]

21:32.334 --> 21:34.684
- We'll call over to the
Mayo Clinic, Sloan Kettering,

21:34.728 --> 21:37.774
see if they'll do the surgery.
- Yeah, worth a try.

21:37.818 --> 21:40.299
I'm gonna fill in Isabella.
- Oh, I'll come with you.

21:40.342 --> 21:42.910
- Oh, actually if you don't
mind, I'd like to do it alone.

21:42.953 --> 21:44.390
I sold her on this surgery.

21:44.433 --> 21:46.783
It's up to me to tell her
I spoke too soon.

21:46.827 --> 21:48.350
- Okay.
- Thanks.

21:48.394 --> 21:49.612
- Yeah.

21:49.656 --> 21:56.402
<i>♪</i>

22:01.015 --> 22:02.451
<i>[EKG beeping]</i>

22:02.495 --> 22:04.192
- Pull slowly and evenly.

22:04.235 --> 22:06.325
- I am.

22:08.196 --> 22:09.850
- No fragments?

22:09.893 --> 22:12.069
- No.
All clear.

22:14.028 --> 22:18.119
- [sighs]

22:18.162 --> 22:21.165
Okay.
We can move on.

22:23.907 --> 22:26.780
<i>[cautery pen buzzing]</i>

22:26.823 --> 22:28.956
Easy.
- I'm controlling the bleeders.

22:28.999 --> 22:30.436
- No,
you're frying healthy tissue.

22:30.479 --> 22:32.133
- All right, I'm calling
Plastics, they'll finish up.

22:32.176 --> 22:34.048
- No, look.
We're almost done.

22:34.091 --> 22:36.050
I don't have the energy
to start over with someone new.

22:36.093 --> 22:38.182
- Then please let me do my job.

22:38.226 --> 22:40.881
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

22:40.924 --> 22:42.404
- [sighs]

22:42.448 --> 22:46.060
<i>♪</i>

22:46.103 --> 22:49.890
Rather you'd use
absorbable sutures.

22:49.933 --> 22:55.199
- Can you grab 3-0 absorbable
Vicryl sutures off the cart?

22:55.243 --> 22:57.201
- Actually, Monocryl ones
instead of Vicryl.

22:57.245 --> 22:58.420
- We don't have that in the ED.

22:58.464 --> 22:59.900
I'd have to call OR,
have them sent down.

22:59.943 --> 23:02.163
- I just want it done right.
- Me, too.

23:02.206 --> 23:03.512
But second-guessing
every move I make

23:03.556 --> 23:06.167
isn't gonna get us there.

23:06.210 --> 23:09.170
- Fine.
Vicryl will do.

23:09.213 --> 23:11.564
- [sighs]
Yeah.

23:11.607 --> 23:14.175
- All right, let's see.

23:14.218 --> 23:15.437
Okay.

23:15.481 --> 23:17.047
- I'm sorry, Auggie.

23:17.091 --> 23:19.833
I know that we're doing a lot
of poking around.

23:19.876 --> 23:21.922
- It's okay.

23:21.965 --> 23:25.012
I trust you.

23:25.055 --> 23:30.409
<i>♪</i>

23:33.194 --> 23:35.109
- I'm gonna go talk
to Dr. Manning for a minute.

23:35.152 --> 23:36.850
Okay?
- All right.

23:36.893 --> 23:38.242
- Okay.

23:38.286 --> 23:43.552
<i>♪</i>

23:43.596 --> 23:46.120
His liver's failing.
- Yes.

23:46.163 --> 23:48.078
He's stable, though.

23:48.122 --> 23:52.387
Adjusting his meds
will ease his discomfort.

23:52.431 --> 23:54.955
- But?

23:54.998 --> 23:57.871
- It's time to admit him.

23:57.914 --> 24:01.178
Get him on the transplant list.
- [sighs]

24:01.222 --> 24:04.268
I knew this day would come.

24:04.312 --> 24:06.401
I've been preparing.
I thought I'd be ready.

24:06.445 --> 24:07.968
I--
- I know.

24:08.011 --> 24:09.883
It feels like you're alone
right now.

24:09.926 --> 24:11.450
But you're not.

24:11.493 --> 24:15.192
I am here for you, okay?

24:15.236 --> 24:22.243
<i>♪</i>

24:25.899 --> 24:27.248
- Last one.

24:29.555 --> 24:31.034
Good.

24:36.387 --> 24:38.433
The nurse will dress the wound.

24:44.221 --> 24:46.659
That guy's impossible.
On me the entire procedure.

24:46.702 --> 24:48.008
- Yeah.

24:48.051 --> 24:49.575
He is challenging,
I'll give you that.

24:49.618 --> 24:50.880
- And he's a doctor.

24:50.924 --> 24:52.142
If he's reckless
with his own health,

24:52.186 --> 24:53.492
he could be reckless
with patients.

24:53.535 --> 24:55.232
He shouldn't be practicing.

24:55.276 --> 24:58.540
- Well, except that people with
BDD tend to be pretty rational.

24:58.584 --> 25:00.934
I mean, except when it comes
to their own bodies, you know?

25:00.977 --> 25:02.196
And that tracks with Dr. Lowry.

25:02.239 --> 25:03.676
I mean, talking with him,

25:03.719 --> 25:06.156
it's clear that he just doesn't
have the same issue

25:06.200 --> 25:07.636
with his patients
as he does with himself.

25:07.680 --> 25:08.681
- Maybe the medical board

25:08.724 --> 25:10.944
should be the one
to decide that.

25:10.987 --> 25:12.206
- Well...

25:12.249 --> 25:15.078
I think I'm pretty qualified.

25:15.122 --> 25:17.080
- I didn't--

25:18.691 --> 25:21.911
He's more unstable
than you think, Dr. Charles.

25:24.218 --> 25:26.089
- Ooh, look on that face,

25:26.133 --> 25:27.917
I'm guessing
the meeting was a bust.

25:27.961 --> 25:29.571
- Huge.

25:29.615 --> 25:31.225
Doctor over there, Mayfield?

25:31.268 --> 25:32.574
He's got a ton of patients

25:32.618 --> 25:35.011
but he won't share any
unless I pad his pockets.

25:35.055 --> 25:37.361
So I walked out.
- Good.

25:37.405 --> 25:38.580
You shouldn't partner
with someone

25:38.624 --> 25:40.060
who's just in it for a payout.

25:40.103 --> 25:41.235
- Of course, turning him down

25:41.278 --> 25:42.410
means I'm back to square one:

25:42.453 --> 25:44.499
short on candidates.

25:44.543 --> 25:46.066
How'd the rest
of the Med files go?

25:46.109 --> 25:49.025
- I called them all.
There was definite interest.

25:49.069 --> 25:51.288
No one committed, but
I told them you'd follow up.

25:51.332 --> 25:54.422
- Fingers crossed.
- Hey, it was a tough morning.

25:54.465 --> 25:57.120
But Ed Gessner's coming in,
right?

25:57.164 --> 25:58.687
Still a win to be had.

25:58.731 --> 26:01.385
- Yeah, you're right.
Keep looking forward.

26:01.429 --> 26:03.605
- Yeah.

26:03.649 --> 26:05.433
- Maggie,
you've got to understand.

26:05.476 --> 26:07.087
Auggie has a rare blood type

26:07.130 --> 26:10.264
and no family to reach out to
for a direct donation.

26:10.307 --> 26:12.658
- Sharon, please don't be
an administrator right now.

26:12.701 --> 26:15.269
You're my friend.
Just level with me.

26:15.312 --> 26:17.271
How long might it be
before Auggie gets a liver?

26:17.314 --> 26:18.533
- I'm not sure.

26:18.577 --> 26:20.753
Gift of Hope oversees
the transplant list.

26:20.796 --> 26:23.625
The hospital has no influence
over that process.

26:23.669 --> 26:25.627
- But you know the system
inside and out.

26:25.671 --> 26:29.109
Experience must be giving you
some kind of a gut feeling.

26:31.372 --> 26:32.982
<i>♪</i>

26:33.026 --> 26:36.638
- Auggie's not critical, so

26:36.682 --> 26:40.424
I imagine at this point,
he's low on the list.

26:40.468 --> 26:45.081
<i>♪</i>

26:45.125 --> 26:48.128
- So we have to wait
for Auggie to get sicker.

26:48.171 --> 26:51.610
And the donor's liver
is gonna be hard to find.

26:51.653 --> 26:53.350
[sighs]

26:53.394 --> 26:57.398
It might not happen...

26:57.441 --> 26:58.617
will it?

26:58.660 --> 27:00.619
<i>♪</i>

27:00.662 --> 27:04.231
- I don't know, Maggie.

27:04.274 --> 27:05.624
I'm sorry.

27:05.667 --> 27:12.500
<i>♪</i>

27:12.543 --> 27:16.591
- No, I understand.
The spread is extensive.

27:16.635 --> 27:18.201
Yes, mm-hmm.

27:18.245 --> 27:21.683
That is the plan our oncologist
recommended as well.

27:21.727 --> 27:24.207
Okay, thank you, Dr. Webber.

27:25.644 --> 27:28.081
- Dr. Manning.
- Just one sec.

27:28.124 --> 27:30.213
- I'm sorry,
but this can't wait.

27:30.257 --> 27:32.259
[whispering]

27:32.302 --> 27:33.826
- Where?
- 6.

27:33.869 --> 27:39.527
<i>♪</i>

27:39.570 --> 27:41.485
- Oh, my God, Crockett.
You've gone rogue?

27:41.529 --> 27:43.531
Have you lost your mind?

27:43.574 --> 27:47.187
- I've overstepped, okay?
But the bigger issue is this.

27:47.230 --> 27:52.409
Dr. Gillen was right.
Deeper I go, more tumor I find.

27:52.453 --> 27:55.238
- Peritoneal studding,
carcinomatosis.

27:55.282 --> 27:57.240
There's cancer everywhere.
- Yeah.

27:57.284 --> 27:58.589
Her kidneys are overrun.

27:58.633 --> 28:00.374
I mean, my first instinct was
to remove them,

28:00.417 --> 28:01.810
but that'll tie Isabella
to dialysis.

28:01.854 --> 28:03.769
- No way she'd be able
to tolerate the chemo then.

28:03.812 --> 28:05.161
If you can't leave
the kidneys in

28:05.205 --> 28:06.728
and you can't take
the kidneys out,

28:06.772 --> 28:08.556
then what's left?

28:08.599 --> 28:11.080
<i>♪</i>

28:11.124 --> 28:12.734
- Ex-vivo.

28:12.778 --> 28:14.605
Remove one kidney, debulk it of
as much cancer as possible,

28:14.649 --> 28:16.738
then re-implant, re-attach,
and repeat with the other one.

28:16.782 --> 28:19.480
- Crockett, ex-vivo surgeries
are still experimental.

28:19.523 --> 28:21.787
There is no guarantee
the kidneys will work

28:21.830 --> 28:24.180
once you put them back in.

28:24.224 --> 28:25.747
- Maybe.

28:25.791 --> 28:27.227
<i>♪</i>

28:27.270 --> 28:30.534
- You didn't call me up here
to debate this, did you?

28:30.578 --> 28:34.495
- Natalie, if we don't do this,
Isabella dies.

28:34.538 --> 28:41.241
<i>♪</i>

28:41.284 --> 28:45.114
- I'll scrub in.

28:49.423 --> 28:50.729
- Hey.

28:50.772 --> 28:51.904
How'd the follow-up calls go

28:51.947 --> 28:53.035
to the Med patients I reached
out to?

28:53.079 --> 28:54.863
- Two out of eight.
- It's something.

28:54.907 --> 28:56.735
[siren wailing]

28:56.778 --> 28:59.738
- Here he is.
Mr. Gessner.

28:59.781 --> 29:01.696
Hey, Mr. Gessner.
Welcome!

29:01.740 --> 29:04.873
[siren wailing]

29:04.917 --> 29:07.136
[indistinct chatter]
What the hell?

29:07.180 --> 29:09.051
Why isn't the ambo using
the COVID entrance?

29:09.095 --> 29:11.837
- I don't know.
Must be backed up.

29:11.880 --> 29:16.189
- What's he doing?
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

29:16.232 --> 29:17.799
Hey, Mr. Gessner.
Wait, please.

29:17.843 --> 29:19.888
- You said it was safe!
- It is, I swear.

29:19.932 --> 29:22.108
Hey, the ED is nowhere near
the COVID--

29:22.151 --> 29:24.414
- I don't care!
- Please, please don't--

29:24.458 --> 29:26.677
Mr. Gessner!
Hey, I just--just--

29:26.721 --> 29:28.070
[engine turns over]

29:28.114 --> 29:29.419
Okay.

29:29.463 --> 29:32.422
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

29:32.466 --> 29:34.903
<i>♪</i>

29:34.947 --> 29:36.426
[indistinct chatter]

29:36.470 --> 29:38.385
- You can let Commander Choi
know treatment rooms

29:38.428 --> 29:41.344
are being turned over within
ten minutes, as ordered.

29:41.388 --> 29:43.216
- Okay, great.

29:43.259 --> 29:44.870
- While I've got you,

29:44.913 --> 29:46.262
I have a cousin in Rockford
who needs a hand.

29:46.306 --> 29:48.134
Pregnant,
three kids in homeschool.

29:48.177 --> 29:50.092
I know it's a pain, but

29:50.136 --> 29:51.790
can I get a few days off
next week?

29:51.833 --> 29:53.226
- Yeah, sure.

29:53.269 --> 29:55.141
- Grazie, grazie.

29:55.184 --> 29:57.796
La mia famiglia.

29:57.839 --> 30:04.672
<i>♪</i>

30:04.715 --> 30:07.762
- All right.
All done.

30:07.806 --> 30:11.810
You see?
That only took two seconds.

30:11.853 --> 30:14.116
- What's it for?

30:14.160 --> 30:17.119
- To find you a liver.

30:17.163 --> 30:19.948
<i>♪</i>

30:19.992 --> 30:22.124
All right, sweetie.

30:22.168 --> 30:25.475
<i>♪</i>

30:25.519 --> 30:28.304
- Right kidney's looking good.
- Great.

30:28.348 --> 30:29.958
Seems luck is on our side.

30:30.002 --> 30:32.308
Just gotta finish closing
the capsule.

30:32.352 --> 30:35.703
Then we can reimplant
and move on to the other one.

30:35.746 --> 30:38.837
- Dr. Marcel, you scheduled
a central line insertion.

30:38.880 --> 30:41.361
- We had a complication.
Had to expand.

30:41.404 --> 30:43.276
- Okay.

30:43.319 --> 30:44.364
- You scheduled
a central line insertion

30:44.407 --> 30:46.061
as a cover to book the OR?

30:46.105 --> 30:49.195
- I needed the room with
as few questions as possible.

30:49.238 --> 30:51.066
Figured I'd cross this bridge
when I got to it.

30:51.110 --> 30:52.763
- Well, we're there

30:52.807 --> 30:54.765
and it doesn't seem like she's
gonna be looking the other way.

30:54.809 --> 30:57.986
Only a matter of time
before we're found out.

30:58.030 --> 30:59.858
- Yep.
[sighs]

30:59.901 --> 31:01.772
<i>♪</i>

31:01.816 --> 31:04.775
<i>[multiple alarms chiming]</i>

31:04.819 --> 31:06.995
<i>♪</i>

31:07.039 --> 31:08.170
- What are you doing?

31:08.214 --> 31:09.476
- I don't like your wound,
your eversion.

31:09.519 --> 31:10.869
- No, no, no, I closed out
all the dead space.

31:10.912 --> 31:12.087
It'll heal seamlessly.

31:12.131 --> 31:13.349
- The dimples.
They need to be fixed.

31:13.393 --> 31:14.568
- Don't, don't!

31:14.611 --> 31:16.439
- Get off! Get off of me!
- Please, please!

31:16.483 --> 31:18.441
You're hurting yourself!
Need some help in here!

31:18.485 --> 31:20.356
- This is all your fault.
They're not perfect.

31:20.400 --> 31:22.010
- Hey, hey, hey.
Dr. Lowry, Dr. Lowry.

31:22.054 --> 31:24.186
- Soft restraints!
- No restraints, no restraints.

31:24.230 --> 31:27.059
- Get off of me!
- Five of haldol.

31:27.102 --> 31:28.930
- Not yet.
- He needs to be sedated!

31:28.974 --> 31:30.279
- Ethan!

31:30.323 --> 31:31.890
I'm gonna be the one who makes
that call, okay?

31:31.933 --> 31:33.065
Let me handle this.

31:33.108 --> 31:34.849
Hey, hey, Todd.
Look at me, look at me.

31:34.893 --> 31:37.373
Right here.
What's going on, buddy?

31:37.417 --> 31:39.898
Breathe with me, all right?
In through the nose.

31:39.941 --> 31:42.030
[inhales deeply]
Look at me.

31:42.074 --> 31:44.467
- Okay.
- In through the nose.

31:44.511 --> 31:46.382
Out through the mouth.

31:46.426 --> 31:47.993
- I appreciate it.

31:48.036 --> 31:50.778
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

31:50.821 --> 31:53.215
<i>♪</i>

31:53.259 --> 31:54.825
- He's a lot calmer--
- Don't you ever interfere

31:54.869 --> 31:56.349
with the treatment
of my patient again.

31:56.392 --> 31:57.567
- Buddy,
you're way out of line.

31:57.611 --> 31:58.829
- Me?

31:58.873 --> 31:59.918
The guy's ripping himself
to shreds.

31:59.961 --> 32:01.093
I told you he need to be
on a hold.

32:01.136 --> 32:02.790
You shot that down
and here we are.

32:02.833 --> 32:03.965
- That's right.

32:04.009 --> 32:05.097
And locking him up
still isn't the answer.

32:05.140 --> 32:06.446
Neither are restraints
or sedatives.

32:06.489 --> 32:08.491
- How can you say that?
He's harming himself!

32:08.535 --> 32:09.579
If you would've just helped me,

32:09.623 --> 32:11.233
we wouldn't be
in this situation!

32:11.277 --> 32:18.284
<i>♪</i>

32:33.081 --> 32:34.213
[grunts]

32:34.256 --> 32:41.263
<i>♪</i>

32:43.135 --> 32:45.441
- How's the left kidney?
Pinking up yet?

32:45.485 --> 32:47.226
- No.
Still purple.

32:47.269 --> 32:50.490
Orientation is good, though.
No rotation.

32:50.533 --> 32:52.361
Inflow artery isn't kinked.

32:52.405 --> 32:55.016
- Doppler it.
- Doppler.

32:55.060 --> 32:57.584
<i>[EKG beeping]</i>

32:57.627 --> 32:59.151
- Sounds monophasic.

32:59.194 --> 33:00.979
There's blood flow,
just not enough.

33:01.022 --> 33:03.242
- Okay. Marty,
get her blood pressure up.

33:03.285 --> 33:06.071
5,000 units of heparin,
let's go.

33:06.114 --> 33:09.291
- Meds are in.

33:09.335 --> 33:10.684
- No change.

33:10.727 --> 33:12.294
- Look, we've been able
to resect a lot of tumor.

33:12.338 --> 33:14.296
Two kidneys would be ideal.

33:14.340 --> 33:16.342
One's enough for her
to tolerate chemo.

33:16.385 --> 33:18.126
Last knot.

33:18.170 --> 33:20.607
Snip.

33:20.650 --> 33:21.956
Moment of truth.

33:22.000 --> 33:24.393
Unclamp the vein.

33:24.437 --> 33:26.482
Nice and easy.
Easy, easy.

33:26.526 --> 33:28.658
Then the artery.

33:28.702 --> 33:31.661
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

33:31.705 --> 33:38.886
<i>♪</i>

33:39.408 --> 33:42.933
- It's pinking up.
Strong blood flow.

33:42.977 --> 33:45.893
- There it is.
- [breathes deeply]

33:45.936 --> 33:49.027
<i>♪</i>

33:49.070 --> 33:53.988
- I am going to have you both
fired.

33:54.032 --> 33:55.337
How is she?

33:55.381 --> 33:57.905
- In great shape.
We're about to close.

33:57.948 --> 33:59.559
- Glad to hear it.

33:59.602 --> 34:01.952
Nevertheless,

34:01.996 --> 34:05.086
she's the last patient either
one of you will ever see

34:05.130 --> 34:06.392
at this hospital.

34:06.435 --> 34:12.572
<i>♪</i>

34:16.924 --> 34:19.883
[indistinct PA announcement]

34:21.059 --> 34:24.758
[door latch clicks]
- Dr. Mayfield.

34:24.801 --> 34:26.716
Thanks for seeing me again.
- Course.

34:26.760 --> 34:29.806
Sorry to keep you waiting.
So many patients.

34:29.850 --> 34:31.025
It's always something.

34:31.069 --> 34:32.635
Don't have to tell you that,
though.

34:32.679 --> 34:36.030
I mean, we're all in this
together, right?

34:36.074 --> 34:37.640
- Well, to that end,

34:37.684 --> 34:39.947
I've had some time to reflect
on our earlier conversation.

34:39.990 --> 34:44.517
Realized there's always a way
to find common ground.

34:44.560 --> 34:46.040
I mean, that is,
if you're still interested.

34:46.084 --> 34:47.737
- I am.

34:47.781 --> 34:49.913
Come on in.
We'll talk details.

34:56.529 --> 34:59.140
[knocks on door]
- Yeah.

34:59.184 --> 35:00.750
- Hey.

35:03.623 --> 35:06.060
Um...

35:06.104 --> 35:08.584
I just wanted to apologize
for my behavior.

35:08.628 --> 35:11.544
I overreacted.
- Apology accepted.

35:11.587 --> 35:13.154
Appreciate you coming down.

35:18.681 --> 35:23.077
What did you, uh,
what'd you do to your hand?

35:23.121 --> 35:24.426
- Rough day.

35:24.470 --> 35:27.125
- Tell me about it, right?

35:28.909 --> 35:32.739
- After I, uh...

35:32.782 --> 35:35.742
left your office this morning,

35:35.785 --> 35:37.047
there was a patient,
Drew Corbett.

35:37.091 --> 35:38.614
He died.

35:38.658 --> 35:41.748
Acute respiratory failure.

35:41.791 --> 35:43.097
When Drew coded,

35:43.141 --> 35:48.233
the resident wanted to do
compressions.

35:48.276 --> 35:51.627
But that's against protocol,
so...

35:51.671 --> 35:53.934
I held them back.

35:53.977 --> 35:55.588
- Okay.

35:55.631 --> 36:00.723
<i>♪</i>

36:00.767 --> 36:03.813
- I stood outside the treatment
room and I watched Drew die.

36:03.857 --> 36:10.864
<i>♪</i>

36:14.084 --> 36:15.956
I wanted to pound on his chest.

36:15.999 --> 36:19.829
<i>♪</i>

36:19.873 --> 36:22.136
But I just stood there
and I did nothing.

36:22.180 --> 36:24.617
<i>♪</i>

36:24.660 --> 36:29.012
Same as yesterday,
same as it'll be tomorrow.

36:29.056 --> 36:32.059
- Man, I'm just, uh...

36:32.102 --> 36:34.235
I'm just so sorry
you gotta go through that.

36:34.279 --> 36:36.977
<i>♪</i>

36:37.020 --> 36:39.501
You know,

36:39.545 --> 36:41.503
maybe the reason that you--

36:41.547 --> 36:43.113
you got so upset at Dr. Lowry

36:43.157 --> 36:44.550
is as simple as this.

36:44.593 --> 36:46.029
I mean, it's very easy

36:46.073 --> 36:49.772
to look at body dysmorphic
disorder as physical.

36:49.816 --> 36:50.991
About the body, right?

36:51.034 --> 36:54.995
But it's actually
a control issue, right?

36:55.038 --> 36:57.302
Not unlike...

36:57.345 --> 37:00.174
feeling responsible
for every patient's outcome.

37:00.218 --> 37:01.741
<i>♪</i>

37:01.784 --> 37:07.268
Or wanting to keep an ED
functioning perfectly

37:07.312 --> 37:08.922
in the middle of a pandemic.

37:08.965 --> 37:11.054
- Lives are at stake,
Dr. Charles.

37:11.098 --> 37:13.013
I have to be effective
at what I do.

37:13.056 --> 37:15.624
- Yeah, but what if that's not
always possible?

37:15.668 --> 37:18.671
- So what?
I'm just supposed to give up?

37:18.714 --> 37:21.717
Accept failure?
- No.

37:21.761 --> 37:23.676
Accept--

37:23.719 --> 37:25.068
accept being mortal.

37:25.112 --> 37:28.855
<i>♪</i>

37:28.898 --> 37:32.075
Remember when we were
dealing with your PTSD?

37:32.119 --> 37:36.297
The, um, the serenity prayer.

37:36.341 --> 37:38.995
How did, uh--
how'd that go again?

37:39.039 --> 37:40.301
- "Grant me the serenity

37:40.345 --> 37:44.305
"to accept the things
that I cannot change,

37:44.349 --> 37:47.221
the courage to change
the things I can..."

37:47.265 --> 37:50.268
- And?

37:50.311 --> 37:52.705
- "And wisdom
to know the difference."

37:52.748 --> 37:57.797
<i>♪</i>

37:57.840 --> 38:00.800
<i>- But even if they put his DNA
into their database,</i>

38:00.843 --> 38:02.976
<i>doesn't it take a really long
time to get the results back?</i>

38:03.019 --> 38:06.588
- I'm expediting the order.
Rush processing.

38:06.632 --> 38:07.894
I mean,
it's gonna cost us triple,

38:07.937 --> 38:09.374
but we'll have an answer
by this week.

38:09.417 --> 38:12.725
<i>- I realize Auggie is low
on the transplant list,</i>

38:12.768 --> 38:13.856
<i>but pinning our hopes</i>

38:13.900 --> 38:15.336
<i>on finding
some long-lost relative?</i>

38:15.380 --> 38:18.774
- Ben, the internet is flooded
with stories of people

38:18.818 --> 38:22.125
who have found family members
through DNA databases.

38:22.169 --> 38:25.303
This is gonna work. <i>
- How can you be so sure?</i>

38:25.346 --> 38:28.958
- Because...it has to.

38:29.002 --> 38:36.009
<i>♪</i>

38:39.404 --> 38:41.362
- You get Goodwin's text?

38:41.406 --> 38:45.366
- "My office, now."

38:45.410 --> 38:47.760
So I guess this is it.
[both sigh]

38:47.803 --> 38:49.805
- Yep.
Let's get this over with.

38:49.849 --> 38:51.503
- Okay.

38:51.546 --> 38:56.986
You know, Manning, I put you in
an impossible position today.

38:57.030 --> 38:59.032
When Goodwin lays the hammer,
I take the fall.

38:59.075 --> 39:01.295
- Noble.

39:01.339 --> 39:02.949
But I chose to scrub in
with you,

39:02.992 --> 39:05.212
so whatever happens,
happens to us both.

39:07.780 --> 39:09.738
[softly]
Okay.

39:12.132 --> 39:13.960
- I don't even know where
to begin.

39:14.003 --> 39:17.355
My dismay at the risk you put
your patient in,

39:17.398 --> 39:19.313
or the headache I have

39:19.357 --> 39:24.971
from Dr. Gillen screaming about
how furious she is.

39:25.014 --> 39:30.368
And by the way,
her anger is justified.

39:30.411 --> 39:33.719
That said--
[chuckles]

39:33.762 --> 39:36.678
incredible job.

39:36.722 --> 39:39.246
- We're not fired?
- Trust me...

39:39.289 --> 39:41.727
you came very, very close.

39:41.770 --> 39:43.424
The board was with Dr. Gillen.

39:43.468 --> 39:45.818
They wanted to see you two
gone.

39:45.861 --> 39:47.297
But I helped them see

39:47.341 --> 39:50.910
there's no PR value
in a successful ex-vivo surgery

39:50.953 --> 39:53.782
if you fire the two heroes
of the day.

39:53.826 --> 39:57.743
- Thank you, Ms. Goodwin.
Thank you.

39:57.786 --> 40:00.354
- Hey, Ma. Ready to go home?
- Yeah.

40:00.398 --> 40:02.443
<i>♪</i>

40:02.487 --> 40:04.097
Get outta here.

40:04.140 --> 40:06.273
- Ma'am.
- Good night.

40:06.316 --> 40:12.322
<i>♪</i>

40:12.366 --> 40:16.065
- Oh, so that's where
you've been.

40:16.109 --> 40:18.241
You okay?

40:18.285 --> 40:19.852
- It is what it is.

40:19.895 --> 40:23.377
But 100 patient files here
and more on the way.

40:23.421 --> 40:25.161
- Still, I'm sorry.

40:25.205 --> 40:27.860
I know you had to make a deal
you didn't really want to.

40:27.903 --> 40:31.080
- End of the day,
it's about saving lives

40:31.124 --> 40:33.735
The trial needs a chance
to prove the drug can work.

40:33.779 --> 40:35.476
Mayfield's patients
guarantee that.

40:35.520 --> 40:38.000
- Well, I am done for the day.

40:38.044 --> 40:41.395
I can help you start
sorting through those files.

40:41.439 --> 40:43.832
- Thanks, April.

40:43.876 --> 40:49.838
<i>♪</i>

40:49.882 --> 40:52.058
- Oh, my God, I thought
it was over for us today.

40:52.101 --> 40:54.277
- Yeah, me too.
[both chuckling]

40:54.321 --> 41:01.328
<i>♪</i>

41:21.914 --> 41:51.073
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

41:51.117 --> 41:54.120
[wolf howls]
